WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:27.600
All right, so we're going to start our second recording

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:30.520
on book one of The Gay Science.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:35.580
I'm Nathaniel, here as ever with John Muckelbauer and Nate DeProspo.

00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:41.160
We're trying something new that came up in our last recording,

00:00:41.620 --> 00:00:45.020
and rather than move on from book two to book one,

00:00:45.140 --> 00:00:47.220
we are going to sit with this for a little bit.

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:50.680
We're going to follow Nietzsche's advice and ruminate,

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:54.340
digest book one a little bit more.

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:58.500
And so, Nate, John, where did the rumination leave you?

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.320
How was this experiment for you?

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:03.340
I mean, I'm not really concerned with repeating ourselves necessarily.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:06.000
I just don't want to focus on the exact spots

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
that we were doing in that first episode.

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:13.660
So I ended up kind of moving towards the latter end of book one.

00:01:14.340 --> 00:01:17.860
I did the same kind of thing because every time,

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:20.500
for obvious reasons, every time that you do this,

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:23.700
you start at the beginning of book one and you read through to the end of book one.

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:26.940
So I consciously started in the middle of book one

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:29.080
and read to the end and then went back to the beginning.

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:34.360
So just to kind of be fresh on the middle or later stuff.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:36.780
I also, just as a side note to start,

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.660
I find myself kind of trying to,

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:44.880
resisting my kind of Hegelianism as I'm reading this

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:47.300
because I finished the dis, obviously,

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:49.160
and we don't have to talk about any of that.

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:51.880
But I find when I read Nietzsche,

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:54.000
my inclination is to be like,

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:55.500
oh, that's where it's Hegelian.

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:56.840
You know, which is not really,

00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:58.460
that shouldn't be the point of just like,

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:00.400
oh, look, he's making a Hegelian point.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:01.100
Because obviously,

00:02:01.700 --> 00:02:04.600
all of philosophy is in some way indebted,

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:05.720
at least tangentially,

00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:08.320
to the kind of Hegelian line.

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:14.280
So I've been straining to find a different interpretive lens

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:16.180
when I look at Nietzsche's writing.

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:17.080
But it's hard for me

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:20.160
because all the parts that attract me to Nietzsche

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:22.620
are also kind of what attract me to Hegel.

00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:26.440
So it's hard for me to differentiate the dispositions at this point.

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:29.740
Like, for example,

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:31.940
what do you call these?

00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:33.560
Like stanzas?

00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:34.000
Aphorisms.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:34.940
Aphorisms, right.

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:37.840
So number 26, for example,

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:41.380
is a really short one on page 100 for me.

00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:41.800
Yeah.

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:43.080
Where he's talking about, you know,

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:44.000
What is life?

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:45.000
Life, that is.

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:47.540
Continually shedding something that wants to die.

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:48.900
Life, that is.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:50.360
Being cruel and inexorable

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:51.700
